segments.text: First, Dr. Jones, tell us something about your early life, including the names and dates and places of birth of your parents, something about your parents, if you can remember, and then the name, I mean, the place and date of your birth and the schools you attended before you went off to college.
Starting in with my parents, father was born almost in Galveston, but it happened early in New York City.
And then mother had to get down to Galveston in the process of the Civil War and had to run the barricade to get into Galveston where my grandfather, who went to Galveston in 1838 as a watchmaker,
held forth as a defense captain.
And she was on a sailing vessel and tried to, and got into port and they bothered, they couldn't find him.
Finally they looked around and found that in those days where they wore a hoop skirt, he was under the hoop skirt.
And the life during the Civil War was rather uneventful.
But after that, his family, father's family, moved up into Saratoga, New York, where he had some property.
And when father got old enough, he went to college at what was then a small Presbyterian college, Princeton, New Jersey.
And as soon as he got out, he came into Texas
because he couldn't get Galveston out of his mind.

But the competition was so heavy that he went up to San Marcos in 1883 and opened up a, what was very rare in those days, an ice making machinery, ice factory, where they had to distill the water in order to get it to freeze quick enough because their condensing process wasn't what it became later.
He went from there into

at the friend of Frank Ball of Galveston into Temple, 1887, opened up the Temple National Bank, where he was president and part owner, and kept in there, and then he helped open up the First National Bank of McGregor.
Shortly after that, he married
in 1889, the daughter of the president of Baylor Female College, which had just moved from, had previously moved from old Independence in Washington County up to Belton, Texas.
And 1889, 1894, I was born in a town of about 3,200, which
The later friends that we had in other states said I was born in the black land prairie dirt between my toes.
They called it mud.
I helped, was able to be in a neighborhood where the boys were pretty well schooled with catch-as-catch-can type of living.
learned to pick cotton, learned to chop cotton, learned to herd cows.
Father took up a little ranch in New Mexico, but continued to live in Temple.
By virtue of getting a scholarship, I was able to go to Princeton in 1913, graduated in 1917, and
get into the 10th Engineers.
What was your major at Princeton?
Geology.
How did you happen to pick that field?
Due to father.
He was a forest, they called him a forest enthusiast.
His enemies called him a forest nut.
And the media's called him a conservation something.
Because whenever they'd have a big rain in Bell County, the muddy water run down, somebody would
hilariously caught him up and said, Jones, Bell County's washing into the Gulf.

The Temple is on a branch of the Leon, which goes into Little River, which goes into the Brazos, which is known to have had the biggest rise of any tributary of the Brazos in recorded history, because in 19, I believe,
It was either 1921 or 1919.
Little River rose to such an extent that the Brazzers River ran uphill from a place west of Huron on the Brazzers where it runs over the rocks.

uphill and many of the local settlers in that area thought earth had come to an end for the river run uphill well he was familiar with all that history and passed it on to us and after the first world war i was been transferred into this into the service of the rear where i'd come in close contact with what europe did with their
conservation work with Forrest, was able to get a job under Mr. Seakey at A&M.
You did serve in Europe then during the First World War.
Eighteen months.
In what area?
Mostly from the standpoint of survival in the service of the rear, in production of railroad ties and aircraft.

stakes for the front and narrow gauge equipment and temporary huts for use at the front and was able and was fortunate enough to get on a logging crew with Minnesota Lumberjacks where in spite of my size I held my own in a four-man crew in the daily
production.
So I would guess from what you said, at that point Western Europe was somewhat ahead of us in conservation.
Oh my gosh, pardon me, eliminate that.
His father, who had married a German girl in 1890, he had taken my, my grandfather had taken my father into the forest of Germany
just as a matter of interest to study the Schwarzwald Black Forest.
And he became a forest enthusiast and was appointed the first individual in Texas to study the extent of the forest area of East Texas, some 21,000 acres, I think.
I'm mixed up now on my area.

of East Texas, and as a result of that, he was able to get, with the aid of Dr. Bissell, who helped him compose the ticket, he was able to get Jim Ferguson to create a State Department of Forestry in 1914.
Was your father appointed to study the forest area of East Texas by the state of Texas?
No, by the National Forest Service.
U.S. Forest Service.
Without stipend.
And he was that enthusiastic, he used his own funds to canvas the legislature.
And against odds, such as one of the legislators said, Jones, he said, what are you going to make out of this if it's passed, this bill on forestry?
But he didn't make anything out of it.
In fact, he gave to it.
But with that interest, he thought that maybe it would be a good thing if I went into that.
And Mr. Seakey gave me a job with Forestry.
in charge of the so-called forest fire prevention work in 1919.
I was able in first division to get out in April 1919 and got quite interested in it but began to see the advantage of a background in agriculture.
Got a
an assistantship under Dr. J. O. Morgan, head of the Department of Agronomy.
That's here at Texas A&M.
At A&M in the fall of 1919 and another assistantship due to having written some editorials and letters from the people in the Houston Tribune on defense of the YMCA and

right in the first world war so i served as assistant secretary of the y and also as assistant in agronomy from 1919 to 21. became general secretary of ymc 21 to 22 and then got our wanderlust and start teaching in houston and mathematics 23 and came back to teach under dr humbert chemistry
freshman chemistry in the fall of 1923, which was quite a varied background.
Yes, it was.

I coached, I organized a wrestling team here in the fall of 1919, just out of having created a general interest from a man as small as I was to have made a public demonstration for the tea club with Oscar Frazier, who was a middleweight.
interested the students enough to ask for a team.
There had not been one before I think.

No, there had been some interest in it, but we didn't even have mats and we were able through various means to get some mats and in the old chapel we had our workout place and for three years we had a recognized varsity team and tied Oklahoma A&M in the spring of
22, we got three first, they got three first, TU got one first.
When you started your classes at A&M for your master's, did you then leave the employment of the Forest Service?
Yes.
So you said you were an assistant in agronomy plus assistant secretary of the Y, so you had two, in a sense, two jobs plus taking courses.
If I'd been a better
had devoted more time to wrestling.
As a letter sport, it would have remained, but it didn't give it enough time after that first three years.
You indicated that you taught chemistry for one year.
Had you had some chemistry background when you were working on your bachelor's, I take it?
Yes, both as bachelor's and as master's degree.
OK.
I believe I picked up in a newspaper somewhere that you organized a Boy Scout troop in 1923.
Yeah, we had the first Boy Scout troop in College Station.
And outside of three months, the first one in the county.
Dr. Barron beat me too, having the first in the county.
I gather then that at that point, certainly most of the boys must have been children of faculty members.
Yes.
Had you been a Boy Scout in your younger life?
No, I had seen the first Boy Scouts organized in 19...
I think 1921.
It wasn't too old prior to that.
It brought over from England, and we had two scout organizations at that time.
One survived, the Scouts of America.
And so, well, I gather that you left the campus pretty soon after that, though, didn't you, to go on to Cornell for your doctorate?
Yes.
I had a friend who was also named Jones, the boys called him Head End Jones, initialed with B.C.
Jones, a late B.C.

Jones, died two years ago, three years ago, who was a good friend in chemistry, and I had taught a year in Houston, Central High, and enjoyed teaching so much, and he said that you never get anywhere unless you go and do graduate work.
for a doctorate degree.
So I took that advice and entered Cornell University with a scholarship.
Let's talk a little bit more about your master's work at A&M.
At that point, of course, this was prior to the creation of the graduate school.
Yes.
How did, who then awarded your degree or?
Dr. J.O.
Morgan was head of agronomy and was also a graduate of Cornell and a very able and enthusiastic advisor and gave me a lot of boost in my research work of all things in buckwheat or which
economically didn't fit this climate enough to become a major factor.
That was the research for your dissertation?
Yes, sir.
Here?
Here, yeah.
Was your degree then, I take it, would have come from the College of Agriculture rather than since there was no graduate school?
Yes, sir.
Dean Pereira and I had several very pleasant
Quentin Ships as did Dr. Fraps in the chemical work that I did.
Did you have to do a proposal for your thesis?
And Dr. Hedges, of course.
Did you have to do a written proposal for your thesis work?
Yes, sir.
And had, but I didn't have to pass, for the master's I didn't have to pass any language.
But having learned German from the time I was seven years old, it helped me quite a bit in
in my language requirement at Cornell, and the French in the Army helped quite a bit in the two language requirement at that time.
Your thesis proposal then, who would you submit that to?
The head of the agronomy department?
Yes, it was to go to Casper Allen Wood, who in turn had
We had Mr. Casper Allen Wood and Dr. J.O.
Morgan as the two advisors on it and for the minor, Dr. C.C.
Hedges.
I was aware that you had your master's from here and I checked and we do have a copy of your thesis back on file.
It's still there with all the pictures in it.
Let's see, was one of your faculty members here some influence in your decision to go to Cornell?

Dr. Morgan, it wasn't too easy at that time to get a fellowship, but Dr. Morgan was very helpful in getting his personal friend, Dr. T. Littleton Lyons and Dr. Harry O. Buckman to get that, to get me into Cornell.
And then what did you continue, you continued with agronomy at that point?
Yes, we called it later soil science.
So did you have some arrangement whereby you could come back to A&M once you completed your dissertation, your degree, or was it sort of by accident that you were able to come back?
I was given, Dr. Morgan said he would like to have me on the staff,
But that's as far as it went.
And at that time and that summer, I started out at University of Colorado, where incidentally I met my wife the summer of 24.
And I took physical chemistry there, differential integral equations and calculus there.
And I found out I didn't decide.
With all that chemistry seemed to offer then, I decided to take Dr. Morgan's and Joan's advice and take agronomy.
And I went on the way east.
I sold my car in Boulder.
And on my way east, I stopped at University of Nebraska, University of Minnesota, Wisconsin U, University of Illinois.
University of Ohio to Columbia and Yale to see what I might like there.

I had an uncle, I mean a cousin-uncle, my father's cousin at Yale at Dean, but I had too many antipathies from undergraduate work there, but I wound up at a place, the only place where I had lost my honors for an
an intercollegiate championship to a Cornell man.
That's where I decided to stay.
They wouldn't promise me a thing as to the length of time it would take to get a graduate degree at all.
But they did take me on, I was happy to say.
And so what, you were there, what, four years?
Three.
Three.
At which time?
Counting the summers, I was three years.
Uh-huh.
At which time you had the doctor's degree then?
I had to do a little extra afterwards.
I got the conferring of the degree in 27.
Okay, then you came here then in 26?
Yes.
Back to the agronomy department?
Yes.
Were you appointed, what, as an instructor, or did you have a higher ranking than that?
Dr. Morgan gave me a tentative professorship, which was later.
under Dean Carl was verified as a professor.
And the highest I got ever was an acting head.
And I may honestly say that's as much as I ever deserved.
He was acting head of the agronomy department.
For two sessions, the first 1933 and the second time 1944.
The agronomy department retained that same name as agronomy the whole time you were in it, did it not?
From 26 through 52.
It was later that it became soil science, soil and crop science section within that.
What courses did you teach in agronomy?
One of my students, who later became a graduate student,
worked with me and we started the first course in soil conservation, 1934, and Red Thompson, Lewis Thompson, who's now dean, associate dean at Iowa State University.
And I taught the course in soil conservation, general soils, which
While I was in A&M, as a teacher, it was required two graduate courses, soil technology and soil management.
And I filled in during the Depression in helping Professor Muldford in 105 agronomy.
So that's crops.
Did you have a number of graduate students working under you at different times?
Yes, we had one of the captain of the track team, Hammonds, Schultz from Houston County.
Strange to say Houston isn't in Houston County.
Van Tine, who, with my help, we started one on the transpiration ratio of cotton, and I regret exceedingly we didn't publish the results due to some unfortunate occurrences.
We did three years of work on that where we used 55-gallon drums, 12 of them, for replications.
And I found that the water requirement of a cotton plant was about 105, but we never did publish it.
The water requirement?
Of a cotton plant, meaning it would take 105 pounds of water for every pound of cotton plant, which at that time was, we didn't find too much work on that particular specific problem.
He was a very remarkable graduate student, but he unfortunately didn't get to finish his work, and I didn't either.
Was this discovery that you made as the amount of water necessary, I guess what, to produce a pound of cotton?
Yes, the whole plant, including the very minor lint and seed.
this would be, what, helpful to people in determining how much water to use for irrigation?
It is used, but in the Rio Grande Valley, through trial and error, they found approximately that amount.
It varies, of course, according to the relative humidity.
What about the type?
Does the type of soil have any bearing on it?
The physical condition of the soil would be important.
By that, you mean the amount of humus in the soil or?
Well, whether it's a sandy loam over a clay or a sandy loam over a sandy clay.
This soil here has been referred to as the Lord put here to tie the Blackland Prairies to the East Texas sandy land.
because of our in-Fergus gray clay subsoil.
While you were on the teaching faculty, did you also do some individual research on your own that is other than assisting graduate students with their research?
In my first years,

I was president of the Science Seminar and then later the Social Science Seminar and did slide them out of a little bit of writing but in productive research that would where we use the the biometrical methods to determine the quality of it I did I tried to
I was an assistant with Dr. Ralph Stewart and Dr. Reeves in working on certain ecological plant relationships.
One of them, the bull nettle, where my main interest was is where you found the bull nettle, you would find the deep sandy soil.
And otherwise, the value that bull nettle might produce in making a tapioca.
due to that enormous sub-circuit's growth.
But outside of one article in Journal of the American Society of Agronomy, I didn't do any.
But you did do a lot of supervising of research.
Quite a bit, and was admitted to the American Association for the Advancement of Science in Texas.
I was made a fellow in the American Association for the Advancement of Science and a fellow in the Texas Scientific Association.
I didn't finish what I started.
What was your average teaching load?
Eighteen hours.
Eighteen hours, which meant that there was not a whole lot of time for research.
To be a good teacher, using Watergate terminology, from my view, a man ought not to have in the soil size more than 25 to 30 students at one time in one class, both from the
pleasure of teaching standpoint and the communication with the students standpoint.
And where you lecture the classes of 65 to 140, you lose that, I don't know, as part of that personal relationship.
I would certainly think you would, yes.
Some of the plentiest classes I had was when we were crowded and I had classes of 25 to 30 and
top deck of Goodwin Hall where I could remember every boy's name and his face and his background.
And the size of the class, I take it, was limited by the size of the room.
Yes.
I believe I remember having seen a clipping about you that indicated that as of a certain date, and I guess it was about your retirement time, that you had
had at one time or another had about 95% of the agronomy graduates, I believe, in one of your courses.
Yes, that was in the advanced soil management.
